{"title_page": "Eat You Alive", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Eat You Alive\n| cover      = LBeatyoualive.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Limp Bizkit]]\n| album      = [[Results May Vary]]\n| released   = 18 June 2003\n| format     = [[Compact disc|CD]]\n| recorded   = 2003\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n* [[Nu metal]]\n* [[post-grunge]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| writer     =\n* Mike Smith\n* Fred Durst\n* Sam Rivers\n* John Otto\n| producer   =\n* [[Fred Durst]]\n* [[DJ Lethal]]\n| prev_title = [[Boiler (song)|Boiler]]\n| prev_year  = 2001\n| next_title = [[Behind Blue Eyes#Limp Bizkit cover|Behind Blue Eyes]]\n| next_year  = 2003\n}}\n\n\"'''Eat You Alive'''\" is a song by the band [[Limp Bizkit]]. It was released in  2003 as a single from their fourth studio album ''[[Results May Vary]]'' (2003). The song was written by [[Fred Durst]], [[John Otto (drummer)|John Otto]], [[Sam Rivers (bassist)|Sam Rivers]] and [[Mike Smith (guitarist)|Mike Smith]], and is Limp Bizkit's first single without [[Wes Borland]], who had left the band in 2001.\n\n== Release and reception ==\nIn promotion of the single, Durst filmed a [[music video]] featuring known actors [[Thora Birch]] and [[Bill Paxton]].<ref name=Erlewine>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/results-may-vary-r657916/review |title=''Results May Vary'' - Limp Bizkit |author=Erlewine, Stephen Thomas |website=Allmusic |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000200/bio |title=Bill Paxton Biography |publisher=imdb |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref> The single peaked at number 16 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]] chart.<ref name=Charts>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/limp-bizkit-p213327/charts-awards/billboard-singles |title=Limp Bizkit - Charts & Awards |website=Allmusic |accessdate=8 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Allmusic]] gave the single one out of five stars.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/eat-you-alive-r660519 |title=Eat You Alive - Limp Bizkit |website=Allmusic |accessdate=8 January 2012}}</ref> A 2004 readers poll published by ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' tied \"Eat You Alive\" with \"[[Headstrong (Trapt song)|Headstrong]]\" by [[Trapt]] and \"[[Me Against the Music]]\" by [[Britney Spears]] as \"worst song\".<ref>{{cite journal |title=Bad to the Bone |journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |volume=20 |issue=3 |page=67 |publisher=SPIN Media |date=March 2004 |url= |accessdate= }}</ref>\n\n\"Eat You Alive\" was included on the compilations ''[[Greatest Hitz (Limp Bizkit album)|Greatest Hitz]]'' (2005),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/greatest-hitz-r806177/review |title=''Greatest Hitz'' - Limp Bizkit |last1=Thomas Erlewine |first1=Stephen |website=Allmusic |accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref> ''[[Collected (Limp Bizkit album)|Collected]]'' (2008)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-collected-r1385351/review |title=''Collected'' - Limp Bizkit |last1=Christopher Monger |first1=James |website=Allmusic |accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref> and ''[[Icon (Limp Bizkit album)|Icon]]'' (2011).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/icon-r2212178/review |title=''Icon'' - Limp Bizkit |last1=Thomas Erlewine |first1=Stephen |website=Allmusic |accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n\n{{Track listing\n| total_length    = 12:03\n\n| title1          = Eat You Alive\n| length1         = 4:12\n\n| title2          = Shot\n| length2         = 3:47\n\n| title3 = Just Drop Dead\n| length3 = 4:04\n}}\n\n==Chart performance==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (2003)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|30|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|16|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|12|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia|15|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive}}\n|-\n|Brazil ([[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Brasileira dos Produtores de Discos|ABPD]])<ref name=\"Brazil\">{{cite web |url = http://asdfg-menezes.org/bookBR.pdf |title = Brazil |work = ABPD |date = October 6, 2001 |accessdate = April 1, 2014 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|59\n|-\n{{singlechart|Denmark|19|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive}}\n|-\n|align='left'|Finland ([[The Official Finnish Charts|Suomen virallinen lista]])\n|align=\"center\"|15\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|16|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive|accessdate=2010-10-25}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|13|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive|songid=5787|accessdate=2019-05-22}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])<ref>[http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement Search for Irish peaks] {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/5hFf8iFDu?url=http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement |date=2009-06-03 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|27\n|-\n{{singlechart|Italy|20|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|36|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=My Way}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|41|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=My Way}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Norway|17|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive|accessdate=2010-10-25}}\n|-\n|align='left'|Spain ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|PROMUSICAE]])\n|align=\"center\"|12\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|31|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=My Way}}\n|-\n|Poland ([[SLiP]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://radioszczecin.pl/index.php?idp=154&idx=1817&idl=646|title=Notowanie nr646|publisher=[[Szczeci\u0144ska Lista Przeboj\u00f3w|SLiP]]|language=Polish|date=2003-10-18|accessdate=2019-03-10}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|36\n|-\n{{singlechart|Swiss|31|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=My Way}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|UK Singles ([[The Official Charts Company]])\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''Billboard'' Alternative Songs\n|align=\"center\"|20\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks\n|align=\"center\"|16\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{youtube|9-27AIozUoQ|\"Eat You Alive (Extended Version)\" Official music video}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|limp-bizkit|eat-you-alive}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Limp Bizkit}}\n\n[[Category:2003 singles]]\n[[Category:2003 songs]]\n[[Category:Limp Bizkit songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about sexuality]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Eat You Alive\n| cover      = LBeatyoualive.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Limp Bizkit]]\n| album      = [[Results May Vary]]\n| released   = September 15, 2003\n| format     = [[Compact disc|CD]]\n| recorded   = 2003\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n* [[Nu metal]]\n* [[post-grunge]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| writer     =\n* Mike Smith\n* Fred Durst\n* Sam Rivers\n* John Otto\n| producer   =\n* [[Fred Durst]]\n* [[DJ Lethal]]\n| prev_title = [[Boiler (song)|Boiler]]\n| prev_year  = 2001\n| next_title = [[Behind Blue Eyes#Limp Bizkit cover|Behind Blue Eyes]]\n| next_year  = 2003\n}}\n\n\"'''Eat You Alive'''\" is a song by the band [[Limp Bizkit]]. It was released in September 2003 as a single from their fourth studio album ''[[Results May Vary]]'' (2003). The song was written by [[Fred Durst]], [[John Otto (drummer)|John Otto]], [[Sam Rivers (bassist)|Sam Rivers]] and [[Mike Smith (guitarist)|Mike Smith]], and is Limp Bizkit's first single without [[Wes Borland]], who had left the band in 2001.\n\n== Release and reception ==\nIn promotion of the single, Durst filmed a [[music video]] featuring known actors [[Thora Birch]] and [[Bill Paxton]].<ref name=Erlewine>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/results-may-vary-r657916/review |title=''Results May Vary'' - Limp Bizkit |author=Erlewine, Stephen Thomas |website=Allmusic |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000200/bio |title=Bill Paxton Biography |publisher=imdb |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref> The single peaked at number 16 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]] chart.<ref name=Charts>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/limp-bizkit-p213327/charts-awards/billboard-singles |title=Limp Bizkit - Charts & Awards |website=Allmusic |accessdate=8 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Allmusic]] gave the single one out of five stars.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/eat-you-alive-r660519 |title=Eat You Alive - Limp Bizkit |website=Allmusic |accessdate=8 January 2012}}</ref> A 2004 readers poll published by ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' tied \"Eat You Alive\" with \"[[Headstrong (Trapt song)|Headstrong]]\" by [[Trapt]] and \"[[Me Against the Music]]\" by [[Britney Spears]] as \"worst song\".<ref>{{cite journal |title=Bad to the Bone |journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |volume=20 |issue=3 |page=67 |publisher=SPIN Media |date=March 2004 |url= |accessdate= }}</ref>\n\n\"Eat You Alive\" was included on the compilations ''[[Greatest Hitz (Limp Bizkit album)|Greatest Hitz]]'' (2005),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/greatest-hitz-r806177/review |title=''Greatest Hitz'' - Limp Bizkit |last1=Thomas Erlewine |first1=Stephen |website=Allmusic |accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref> ''[[Collected (Limp Bizkit album)|Collected]]'' (2008)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-collected-r1385351/review |title=''Collected'' - Limp Bizkit |last1=Christopher Monger |first1=James |website=Allmusic |accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref> and ''[[Icon (Limp Bizkit album)|Icon]]'' (2011).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/icon-r2212178/review |title=''Icon'' - Limp Bizkit |last1=Thomas Erlewine |first1=Stephen |website=Allmusic |accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n\n{{Track listing\n| total_length    = 12:03\n\n| title1          = Eat You Alive\n| length1         = 4:12\n\n| title2          = Shot\n| length2         = 3:47\n\n| title3 = Just Drop Dead\n| length3 = 4:04\n}}\n\n==Chart performance==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (2003)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|30|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|16|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|12|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia|15|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive}}\n|-\n|Brazil ([[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Brasileira dos Produtores de Discos|ABPD]])<ref name=\"Brazil\">{{cite web |url = http://asdfg-menezes.org/bookBR.pdf |title = Brazil |work = ABPD |date = October 6, 2001 |accessdate = April 1, 2014 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|59\n|-\n{{singlechart|Denmark|19|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive}}\n|-\n|align='left'|Finland ([[The Official Finnish Charts|Suomen virallinen lista]])\n|align=\"center\"|15\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|16|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive|accessdate=2010-10-25}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|13|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive|songid=5787|accessdate=2019-05-22}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])<ref>[http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement Search for Irish peaks] {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/5hFf8iFDu?url=http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement |date=2009-06-03 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|27\n|-\n{{singlechart|Italy|20|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|36|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=My Way}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|41|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=My Way}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Norway|17|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Eat You Alive|accessdate=2010-10-25}}\n|-\n|align='left'|Spain ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|PROMUSICAE]])\n|align=\"center\"|12\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|31|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=My Way}}\n|-\n|Poland ([[SLiP]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://radioszczecin.pl/index.php?idp=154&idx=1817&idl=646|title=Notowanie nr646|publisher=[[Szczeci\u0144ska Lista Przeboj\u00f3w|SLiP]]|language=Polish|date=2003-10-18|accessdate=2019-03-10}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|36\n|-\n{{singlechart|Swiss|31|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=My Way}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|UK Singles ([[The Official Charts Company]])\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''Billboard'' Alternative Songs\n|align=\"center\"|20\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks\n|align=\"center\"|16\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{youtube|9-27AIozUoQ|\"Eat You Alive (Extended Version)\" Official music video}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|limp-bizkit|eat-you-alive}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Limp Bizkit}}\n\n[[Category:2003 singles]]\n[[Category:2003 songs]]\n[[Category:Limp Bizkit songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about sexuality]]\n", "name_user": "31.0.34.232", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eat_You_Alive"}
{"title_page": "Behind Blue Eyes", "text_new": "{{short description|Single by The Who}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Behind Blue Eyes\n| cover      = The Who Behind Blue Eyes.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Belgian single sleeve\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Who]]\n| album      = [[Who's Next]]\n| B-side     = \n*\"[[My Wife]]\" (US)\n*\"[[Going Mobile]]\" (Europe)\n| released   = 6 November 1971\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = May\u2013June 1971<ref>''The Who The Ultimate Collection Liner Notes''</ref>\n| studio     = [[Olympic Studios|Olympic]], London\n| genre      = \n*[[Hard rock]]\n*[[folk rock]]\n| length     =\n*3:41 (album version)\n*3:28 (original version)\n| label      = \n*[[Decca Records|Decca]]\n*[[MCA Records|MCA]]\n*[[Track Records|Track]]\n*[[Polydor Records|Polydor]]\n| writer     = [[Pete Townshend]]\n| producer   = \n*The Who\n*Associate producer: [[Glyn Johns]]\n*Executive producers: [[Kit Lambert]], [[Chris Stamp]], Pete Kameron\n| prev_title = [[Baba O'Riley]]\n| prev_year  = 1971\n| next_title = [[Join Together (song)|Join Together]]\n| next_year  = 1972\n}}\n\n\"'''Behind Blue Eyes'''\" is a song by the English rock band [[the Who]], recorded in 1971. It was the second single from their fifth album ''[[Who's Next]]'' and was originally written by [[Pete Townshend]] for his ''[[Lifehouse (rock opera)|Lifehouse]]'' project.<ref>{{cite web |title = Behind Blue Eyes : The Who |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/196775/review/6067884|work=Rolling Stone |accessdate=16 June 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4433223.stm |title=The Streets lead Ivor nominations |work=BBC News |accessdate=16 June 2008 |date=11 April 2005}}</ref> The song is one of The Who's best-known recordings and has been covered by many artists.\n\n==Background==\n\"Behind Blue Eyes\" originated after a Who concert in [[Denver]] on 9 June 1970.<ref name=linernotes>{{cite web|last1=Cady|first1=Brian|title='Who's Next' liner notes|url=http://www.thewho.net/linernotes/WhosNext.htm|website=The Hypertext Who}}</ref> Following the performance, Townshend became tempted by a female [[groupie]], but he instead went back to his room alone, possibly as a result of the teachings of his spiritual leader, [[Meher Baba]].<ref name=bynumbers /> Upon reaching his room, he began writing a prayer, the first words being \"When my fist clenches, crack it open...\" These words later appeared as lyrics in the \"climactic rocking section\" of \"Behind Blue Eyes.\"<ref name=bynumbers />\n\nWhen \"Behind Blue Eyes\" was to be released as part of the aborted ''Lifehouse'' project, the song was sung from the point of view of the main villain, Jumbo. The lyrics are a first-person lament from Jumbo, who is always angry and full of angst because of all the pressure and temptation that surrounds him, and the song was intended to be his \"theme song\" had the project been successful. Pete Townshend said of the song's lyrics:\n\n{{quote|\"Behind Blue Eyes\" really is off the wall because that was a song sung by the villain of the piece [Jumbo], the fact that he felt in the original story that he was forced into a position of being a villain whereas he felt he was a good guy.<ref name=bynumbers>{{cite book|last1=Grantley|first1=Steve|last2=Parker|first2=Alan|title=The Who by Numbers: The Story of the Who Through Their Music|publisher=Helter Skelter}}</ref>|}}\n\nThe version of \"Behind Blue Eyes\" released on ''[[Who's Next]]'' in 1971 was the second version the band recorded; the first was recorded at the Record Plant in New York on 18 March 1971 and features [[Al Kooper]] on [[Hammond organ]].<ref>Who's Next \u2013 1995 Remastered Edition CD Booklet Page 23</ref> The original version was released as a bonus track on the 1995 CD reissue of ''[[Who's Next]]''.\n\n\"Behind Blue Eyes\" was initially considered for a UK single release, but Townshend claimed that the song was \"too much out of character\" for the British singles market.<ref name=bynumbers /> However, the song did eventually see a single release in France, Belgium, the United States and the Netherlands. Backed with \"[[My Wife]]\" in the US and \"[[Going Mobile]]\" in Europe, the song reached #34 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and #24 on ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]]''.<ref name=linernotes />\n\nPete Townshend has also recorded two solo versions of the song. The original [[Demo (music)|demo]] of the song was featured on the ''[[Scoop (album)|Scoop]]'' album. The demo along with a newer recording of the song featuring an orchestral backing was featured in ''[[The Lifehouse Chronicles]]''.\n\n==Composition==\nThe song starts with a solo voice singing over an [[arpeggio|arpeggiated]] acoustic guitar in the key of [[E minor]], and a bass guitar and ethereal harmonies are added. Eventually, the song breaks out into a full-scale [[rock anthem]], with a second theme being introduced near the end, before a brief reprise of the quieter first theme. Songs written in alternating sections were a feature of Townshend's writing of the period, going back at least to ''[[Tommy (rock opera)|Tommy]]'', where the technique was used in \"[[Christmas (song)|Christmas]]\" and \"[[Go to the Mirror!]]\". The guitar riff at the end of the rock anthem section is also used after the [[bridge (music)|bridge]] during the song \"[[Won't Get Fooled Again]]\", perhaps serving as a link between the two songs when both were intended to be parts of a single rock opera.<!-- About songs written in alternating sections being a trademark, and comparisons to other works. -->\n\n==Chart performance==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1971)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|34|artist=The Who|song=Behind Blue Eyes|artistid=184814|accessdate=2010-10-25|date=2003-12-6}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US [[Cashbox (magazine)|''Cashbox'']]<ref name=linernotes />\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|24\n|}\n\n== Personnel ==\n*[[Roger Daltrey]] \u2013 lead vocals\n*[[Pete Townshend]] \u2013 acoustic and electric guitar, backing vocals\n*[[John Entwistle]] \u2013 bass, backing vocals\n*[[Keith Moon]] \u2013 drums\n\n==In other media==\nA cover was used in the FX television series, ''[[Legion (TV series)|Legion]]'', in season 2, episode 11. The show's creator, [[Noah Hawley]], sings the track with [[Jeff Russo]] on backing vocals as well as any instruments used in the song. However, in the context of the show, [[Dan Stevens]] and [[Navid Negahban]] sing the song in English and [[Persian language|Persian]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Russo |first1=Jeff |title=Legion Cover Album Released: It\u2019s Always Blue |url=http://jeffrusso.com/2018/08/17/legion-cover-album-released-its-always-blue/ |website=Jeff Russo |accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Harley |first1=Nick |title=Legion Season 2 Episode 11 Review: Chapter 19 |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/legion/274197/legion-season-2-episode-11-review-chapter-19 |website=Den of Geek |accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref> There are parallels between the protagonist, [[Legion (Marvel Comics)|David Haller]], and Townshend's character of Jumbo from the original concept of the song as well.\n\n==Limp Bizkit cover==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Behind Blue Eyes\n| cover      = Limp - BBE cover of the single for the cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Limp Bizkit]]\n| album      = [[Results May Vary]]\n| released   = {{start date|df=y|2003|08|10}}\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 2003\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =<!--Do not add unsourced genres -->\n| length     = \n*4:28 (without hidden track)\n*5:58 (album version with hidden track)\n| label      = \n*[[Flip Records (1994)|Flip]]\n*[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| writer     = [[Pete Townshend]]\n| producer   = [[Fred Durst]]\n| prev_title = [[Eat You Alive]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[Home Sweet Home/Bittersweet Symphony]]\n| next_year  = 2005\n}}\n\n\"Behind Blue Eyes\" was covered by American [[rap rock]] group [[Limp Bizkit]]. It was released in 2003 as a single from their album ''[[Results May Vary]]''. Limp Bizkit's arrangement is notable for featuring a [[Speak & Spell (toy)|Speak & Spell]] during the [[bridge (music)|bridge]].<ref name=Erlewine>{{cite web|author=[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/results-may-vary-r657916/review |title=Results May Vary \u2013 Limp Bizkit &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |website=[[AllMusic]] |date= 2003 |accessdate=3 October 2016}}</ref> This, together with a new verse and an extra chorus, replaces the rock theme of The Who's version. The song is followed by a hidden track titled \"All That Easy\", after a few seconds of silence, making the total length 5:58. However, the hidden track is not featured in the single release.\n\nAlthough the cover received mixed reviews and reached only number 71 on the US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]], it was more successful worldwide. It reached number one in Sweden in February 2004, becoming the band's only number-one single there, and charted within the top three in Austria, Denmark, Germany and Norway. Elsewhere in Europe, it became a top-twenty hit in Belgium, France, the Netherlands and Switzerland while peaking at number 18 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. In [[Australasia]], it reached number four in Australia and number five in New Zealand.\n\n===Critical reception===\nLimp Bizkit guitarist [[Wes Borland]], who was not in the band at the time of recording and releasing this cover, made the following comments about the song and video: \"This is probably the worst cover ever, and the video is awful. It's just really embarrasing, and it's so unbelievably self-indulgent. Someone must have really worked out hard to be able to take their shirt off and have Halle Berry make out with them.\"{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} It was also criticized by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine readers, who named it the second-worst cover song of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/rolling-stone-readers-choose-the-worst-cover-songs-of-all-time-12882/10-william-shatner-lucy-in-the-sky-with-diamonds-155039/|title=Rolling Stone Readers Choose the Worst Cover Songs of All Time|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=18 August 2011}}</ref>. [[Sun-Sentinel]], however, praised the cover, saying (along with \u201cBuild a Bridge\u201d) \u201c... prove Durst can do more than just rap.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-2003-11-14-0311130208-story.html|title=A DIFFERENT BIZKIT|first=Brandon Bielich Coral Springs|last=High|website=Sun-Sentinel.com}}</ref>\n\n===Music video===\nThe music video features [[Academy Award]]-winning actress [[Halle Berry]]. It contains scenes from the motion picture ''[[Gothika]]'', in which Berry stars. It depicts Berry and Limp Bizkit's vocalist [[Fred Durst]] in a relationship similar to the storyline of the film. The song also appeared during the credits of the film itself and its music video was also featured as a bonus feature on the DVD release of the film. \n\n===Charts===\n====Weekly charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2003\u20132004)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|4|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Behind Blue Eyes|accessdate=2010-10-25}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|3|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Behind Blue Eyes|accessdate=2010-10-25}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|13|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Behind Blue Eyes|accessdate=2010-10-25}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia|16|artist=Limp Bizkit|song=Behind Blue Eyes|accessdate=2010-10-25}}\n|-\n|Czech Republic ([[IFPI]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Ofici\u00e1ln\u00ed \u010cesk\u00e1 Hitpar\u00e1da - Pro t\u00fdden 25/2004|url=http://www.ifpicr.cz/radio.htm|publisher=IFPI \u010cR|language=Czech|accessdate=2020-